	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Well, seeing as this is the hardware section, I decided to tear apart the retron5 today and take a peek<br /><br />the biggest visible components on the top sides of the boards(I didn't take it all the way apart) are:<br /><br />On the main board:<br />-Rockchip RK3066<br />-2x Nanya ram<br />-29F16G<br /><br />On the cart board:<br />-Xilinx Spartan XC3S50A<br />-4x ALVC164245 which look to be voltage related<br /><br />then there are two skinny boards for the controller ports<br /><br />It looks like the flex cables connecting the boards may have been glued in? strange<br /><br />there's also a couple of through hole resistors connected to a testpoint on one end and a wire on the other that stick out like a sore thumb on what looks to be a late 'revision' to the board<br /><br />edit: <br />Drivers: <br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.rockchip.nl/downloads/">http://www.rockchip.nl/downloads/</a><!-- m --><br />Hold reset and power on while connected with mini usb to PC <br /><br />looks like maybe this is the software you could use to flash it? RKBatchTool<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.mediafire.com/download/koja23446mrl6zb/Rockchip+1.5.zip">http://www.mediafire.com/download/koja2 ... ip+1.5.zip</a><!-- m --><br /><br />[let the hacking begin?]

		

		</td>
